<br>
I think Celestial Rising cover this best, they'll accept level 35 recruits - but as their applications section says - there is nothing in the guild for you at level 35.  You see level in itself is no gauge of the person, only a temporary measurement of a characters power - and excluding people because of it will not necessarily start getting you the 'right' kind of people for your guild.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>2) Have guild powerleveling nights, where people park themselves in TD and I quad spirocs until my eyes bleed.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is a bad idea for two reasons, firstly: Extensive power levelling will leave you with a lot of high level characers who don't know their class very well.  Secondaly, 4 mobs is not enough <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   AOE baby - it's THE way to power level <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
However that should not detract you from spending time with your younger members and hanging out with them, playing with them (be it with an alt or 'helping' their group for an hour or so).  This could be a positive long term investment.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>3) Hook up with a higher level guild and become their junior partner.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
How about hooking up with a guild of similar stature?  There's plenty of pre-epic guilds about who'd love to do them but don't have the numbers.  Individually you are just a bunch of noobs, together your a bunch of zerglings capable of some pretty big corpse runs. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>4) Beg and plead for people to stop playing alts and to level their mains<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Encourage your guild to be incestual, to first LFG within /gu - and to consider leaving groups gracefully for guild offered groups (this is good training for raids).  A member alone is meating other people, but your members together are having other people meet them...<br>
<br>
<br>
In regards to raids organising 'something for everyone' is generally a bad idea.  I bet you'll find the lower levels might come if they are on, stay for a short while and then begin the feel that 'its all just for the high levels, I feel useless, and I feel like i'm giving THEM gear'...  In my view all-level range raids create a THEM and us fealing.<br>
<br>
Once you have established a culture of incestual inter-grouping within your guild then you will find that groups start forming for loot rather than xp. When that happens you are ready to start raiding.<br>
<br>
The strength of a guild comes not from the guild itself but from the members of the guild, encouraging your members to do what the 'guild' wants them to do will just distance you from those members.  Instead the guild should do what the members want - or at least be very clear about it's objectives when recruiting.<br>
<br>
<br>
