<br>
The 50+ you lost are the ones that are probably more focused on loots and gears and progression to high level content.  If you guild is not supporting that or driving towards that, they won't stay one way or another.<br>
<br>
So the key is to really sit down and define what your guild is about, where you plan to go in-game, how you are going to get there, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>and by when</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  When you have that, present that to your members.  Some will stay, some will leave.  But from that point on, only accept those that understand the purpose, goals, and future progression of your guild.<br>
<br>
Getting people to raid level will not necessarily help you to keep people.  You might keep the raiders but you might lose the more causal players.  Remember your core are the people who started the gulid with you.  Start with what you want and what they want.<br>
<br>
As for the other things you've suggested:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>1) tighten up recruiting, and only accept people above a certain level (45 or so?)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Level matters less than play style.  A level 45 can have fun and stay at 45 for months.  A level 20 can be a level 50 in a few weeks.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>2) Have guild powerleveling nights, where people park themselves in TD and I quad spirocs until my eyes bleed.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
In general, never PL people.  The PLed are generally less knowledgable about their classes and often turn into single-role stereotype.  Besides, if you want them to level up and they don't, that means they don't listen to you anyway, what's the point.  And if they can't level up on their own, then what good are they?<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>3) Hook up with a higher level guild and become their junior partner.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
By doing that, you are telling your own guild that the guild can't stand on its own.  Shows no grits.  Its a slap on the face.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>4) Beg and plead for people to stop playing alts and to level their mains<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
This has to do with play style.  You have to start with setting guild goals, the pace of progression, and recruit only those that fit the path.  If a large number of your members play lots of alts, chances are they will never be the raiders that you'd like to see.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
In the end, its all about management.  You cannot just gather a group of people together, slap a guild tag on them and expect progress or unity.  You need to create goals and expectations, and follow through with them.  That gives your applicants and members a roadmap.  They'll either help you along or following another path at different speed and ferocity. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=328193"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.geocities.com/hibashirasakai/HibashiraNewHalfSize.txt"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#deddbf><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub228.ezboard.com/bxevserverboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dlaritan>Dlaritan</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered Member</span><br>  Posts: 51<br> <font color=#330000>(7/29/03 8:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub228.ezboard.com/fxevserverboardsfrm12.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=11.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.usefulware.com/graphics/lines/avatar.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Mid-level guild blues</span><hr size=1> all this advice is, of course, predicated on whether you want to be a raiding guild.  your app process needs to make sure you are getting people who want the SAME THINGS out of their EQ experience.<br>
<br>
If they (your guild) want to play a bunch of chars and have fun doing so, dont push people to level so they can raid, that isnt what they want to do.<br>
<br>
once everyone's goals are the same, everyone knows what the plan is for achieving them, and your recruiting process is bringing in people who have the same goals and are willing to do what it takes according to the plan, you will be in guilded bliss. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=8660" target="top"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.usefulware.com/graphics/lines/sigalone.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Forest Stalker of Karana</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:red;">Dlaritan scowls at you, ready to attack -- He looks like he could wipe the floor with you!</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub228.ezboard.com/bxevserverboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=shamuofxev>shamuofxev</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mu</span><br>  Posts: 400<br> <font color=#330000>(7/29/03 9:23 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub228.ezboard.com/fxevserverboardsfrm12.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=11.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~arithon/EQ/mgosau_sig_commission.GIF WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Mid-level guild blues</span><hr size=1> The split between the &quot;fun and family&quot; guild and the &quot;raiding&quot; guild is nearly impossible to overcome.  There are some &quot;social&quot; guilds that have been around for years (AF and SoH come to mind) with a strict &quot;no mandatory raiding&quot; policy.  And they routinely go through splits, when one generation of players has reached the maximum of what they can achieve in the guild, and move on.  As long as you have a good leadership and good recruiting, you can survive being &quot;non-raiding&quot;, even when you will just loose most of your top end players at some point. If you do it right, you can develop a nice community of ex-members, that will assist your guild in times of need, that feel a common bond having gone through a development phase in their characters that involved your guild.<br>
Now, if you have a consensus you want to develop as a guild towards high end content, you need to make that decission as a guild, and then make it clear at recruiting time to all you add.  Moving up means raids, and raids require time commitment.  The typical starting raid, Kael arena, needs 40 people of 50 average for 3 h. Maybe 30 with today's equipment available even for a level 50.<br>
If you want to move up, you need to make raid attendance mandatory for all on line, you will not be able to get the necessary teamwork going if you have always changing people at your raids.<br>
